solution.p:
We first find the inverse function for y = x^3 + 2 by solving for x:
\begin{align*}
x^3 \amp = y - 2 \amp\amp\text{Substract 2 from both sides.} \\
x \amp = \sqrt[3]{y - 2}\amp\amp\text{Take cube roots.}
\end{align*}
The inverse function is x = f^{-1}(y) = \sqrt[3]{y - 2}. Now we evaluate the inverse function at y = 10:
f^{-1}(10) = \sqrt[3]{10 - 2} = 2

warning.p:
Although the same symbol, ^{-1}, is used for both reciprocals and inverse functions, the two notions are not equivalent. That is, the inverse of a given function is usually not the same as the reciprocal of that function. In , note that f^{-1}(y) is not the same as the reciprocal of f (y), because
\frac{1}{f(y)}= \frac{1}{y^3+ 2} ~~\text{ but }~~ f^{-1}(y)= \sqrt[3]{y - 2}
To avoid confusion, we use the notation \dfrac{1}{f} to refer to the reciprocal of the function f.

ol.li:
We solve P = 12 + 2t^3 for t in terms of P.
\begin{align*}
2t^3 \amp = P - 12\amp\amp\text{Substract 12 from both sides.}\\
t^3 \amp = \frac{P - 12}{2}\amp\amp\text{Divide both sides by 2.}\\
t \amp = \sqrt[3]{\frac{P - 12}{2}}\amp\amp\text{Take cube roots.}
\end{align*}
The inverse function is t = f^{-1}(P) =\sqrt[3]{\dfrac{P - 12}{2}}. It tells us the number of years it takes for the pheasant population to grow to size P.

subsection.p:
 If we apply the function f to a given input value and then apply the function f^{-1} to the output from f, the end result will be the original input value. For example, if we choose t = 5 as an input value, we find that
	\begin{align*}
	f(\alert{5})\amp= 6 + 2(\alert{5}) 
	= \blert{16}\amp\amp\text{ Multiply by 2, then add 6.}\\
	\text{and } f^{-1}(\blert{16}) \amp = \frac{\blert{16} - 6}{2}
	= \alert{5}\amp\amp\text{Subtract 6, then divide by 2.}
	\end{align*}

ol.li:
First evaluate the function f for x = 2:
f(\alert{2}) = \alert{2}^3 + 2 = \blert{10}
Then evaluate the inverse function f^{-1} at y = 10:
f^{-1}(\blert{10}) = \sqrt[3]{\blert{10} - 2} = \sqrt[3]{8}= \alert{2}
We started and ended with 2.

First evaluate the function f^{-1} for y = -25:
f^{-1}(\alert{-25}) = \sqrt[3]{-25 - 2} = \blert{-3}
Then evaluate the function f for x = -3:
f (\blert{-3}) = (\blert{-3})^3 + 2 = \alert{-25}
We started and ended with -25.

subsection.p:
 A graph does not change if we change the names of the variables, so we can let x represent the input for both functions, and let y represent the output. Consider the function C = h(F) from , and its inverse function, F = h^{-1}(C). The formulas for these functions are
	\begin{align*}
	C \amp = h(F) = \frac{5}{9}(F - 32)\\
	F \amp = h^{-1}(C) = 32 + \frac{9}{5}C
	\end{align*}
	But their graphs are the same if we write them as
	\begin{align*}
	y \amp = h(x) =\frac{5}{9}(x - 32)\\
	y \amp= h^{-1}(x) = 32 + \frac{9}{5}x
	\end{align*}
	The graphs are shown in .

When we interchange the input and output variables to obtain the inverse function, we interchange the domain and range of the function. For the functions graphed in , you can see that
\begin{align*}
\text{Domain} (f) \amp=[-4, 12] \amp\text{and}\amp\amp  \text{Domain} ( f^{-1}) \amp= [0, 8]\\
\text{Range} ( f ) \amp = [0, 8] \amp\amp\amp \text{Range} ( f -1) \amp = [-4, 12]
\end{align*}
This relationship between the domain and range of a function and its inverse holds in general.

