Graph the function y = f (x) = \dfrac{1}{x +3} in the window
		\begin{align}
        \text{Xmin} \amp = -6 \amp\amp \text{Xmax} = 3.4\\
        \text{Ymin} \amp = -6 \amp\amp \text{Ymax} = 3
        \end{align}

li.p:
To find the inverse function, we solve for x. Take the reciprocal of both sides of the equation.
\begin{align*}
\dfrac{1}{y} \amp= x + 3\amp\amp\text{Subtract 3 from both sides.}\\
x \amp = \dfrac{1}{y}- 3
\end{align*}
The inverse function is x = f^{-1}(y) = \dfrac{1}{y}- 3, or, using x for the input variable, f^{-1}(x) = \dfrac{1}{x}- 3. The graph of f^{-1} looks like the graph of y = \dfrac{1}{x}, shifted down 3 units, as shown in .
